        <text>This place was perfectly decent. It just felt like it was far away from life. It's attached to a giant, new, and quite uncool feeling mall. But it's all new clean build. It just feels... A but sterile and disconnected from things.</text>

        <rating>4</rating>
        <text>Visited 28/12/2012 - Hotel was opened very recently (3Q2012) and you can even smell fresh paint and see plastic covers in some areas. Access by car can be tricky as this area of Lyon is completely new and not all GPS devices are up to date yet. Very convenient car park with direct access. 8â‚¬ per night only. Confluence shopping mall nearby (no direct access though). Tram line #1 nearby with very convenient direct access to main spots. Note that family tickets are cheap during weekends. You can also rent a bike in VELOV stations nearby (one located at the tram station, one located on the river side). Design rooms. WC are in the bathroom so that it's not very suitable when travelling with family. Shower surrounded by glass so that your room mates will be awaken in the morning by the first one to shower. As we are frequent ACCOR hotels clients, we had a special rate during Xmas 2012 so that quality / price ratio was simply outstanding. Reception desk is rather small considering the size of the hotel. I forgot one small case in the room when leaving and reception desk called me to pick it up. Nice. Breakfast with usual NOVOTEL stuff: scrambled eggs, bacon, ham, cheese, cereals, jelly, bread, coffee, tea, milk (be sure to ask for real milk, not the artificial one coming from the machine!!!), etc. Best rooms have odd numbers and X01 to X17 are even better with a direct view to the SaÃ´ne river, see attached photos. Highly recommended overall.

Room Tip: Rooms with odd numbers will be better. X01 to X17 will be even better due to the view to the river!!!</text>

        <author_name>A Google User</author_name>
        <language>en</language>
        <rating>5</rating>
        <text>A masterpiece. This restaurant is truly something special. When you pull onto the island that this wonderful restaurant calls home, you feel like you have been transported back in time. From the second we walked in the door, we were waited on hand and foot. Our main server, having informed us that he had only worked at Michelin starred restaurants, was incredibly welcoming and informative. He walked my wife and I through the menu, the courses, and the wine flight that we enjoyed along with the meal. The courses built one after another to a beautiful crescendo of flavour and creativity. Hell, we even had house made marshmallows - a first for us. The chef came out to speak with us on two separate occassions, letting us know that he almost married an American girl and that he was happy to have us. He is gracious and supremely talented. Though expensive, Auberge de l'Ile is worth every euro. I hope that they get their third star soon, because they are most deserving. This restaurant truly stands out among the many fabulous restaurants in beautiful Lyon!</text>

134.reviews:
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<reviews>
    <item>
        <aspects>
            <item>
                <rating>0</rating>
                <type>overall</type>
            </item>
        </aspects>
        <author_name>Georgie Burrows</author_name>
        <author_url>https://plus.google.com/104548386693105901105</author_url>
        <language>en</language>
        <profile_photo_url>//lh4.googleusercontent.com/-wlMy6i0JlBM/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAAw/zYiizdqFCLk/photo.jpg</profile_photo_url>
        <rating>1</rating>
        <text>From start to finish this place is  a disaster and has gone majorly down-hill since the last time I went there, about 3 years ago.... there are some positives. 
So after wanting to continue our night on the dancefloor, we decided to continue the night at around 3am at Pinks. Great idea... 
The bouncer on the first door was quite kind (rare in France), he asked for a piece of ID which I found quite strange after living in France so long, maybe I'm just not used to it anymore (however, I am closer to the 30 end of the scale rather than 20!) 
The girl at the cloakroom was nice too. 

So we're inside now after leaving our things in the trusty cloakroom control. First things first let's get a drink- the drinks were reasonably priced in all fairness. Secondly, lets go for a cigarette, the smoking room was small, smokey and dark- pretty standard French fumoir. We got talking to people as you do, a lot of people were paying attention to us because we were speaking English- something we're pretty used to, French people love to speak English when they've had a few to drink. Then all of a sudden this man quite casually gets a little back of cocaine out of his pocket and sniffs it off a card, then washes it down with a few swigs of whiskey (from his own bottle that he kept in his pocket!). Being slightly shocked from this we decide to head straight to the dancefloor, the music was seriously hit and miss, the DJ was terrible and couldn't mix to save his life and there was no "theme" to the music - just random tracks; practically impossible to dance to, even for me! 
The DJ seemed to be a huge fan of dry ice too, which 2 days later I'm sure I can still feel stuck in my throat. Seriously, less is more, especially in a small space like that, it genuinely made me feel really ill!! So I went to the bar to ask for a glass of water- refused point blank. REFUSED a glass of water, isn't that illegal?! So after the bar man deciding to drench me and think it's hilarious (so trash, I'm not 19. and it's -3degrees outside!!) I obviously had to dry off before leaving the place, so time for another dance, the music hadn't really improved. <?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<reviews>
    <item>
        <aspects>
            <item>
                <rating>0</rating>

        </aspects>
        <author_name>Katalin TÃ³th</author_name>
        <author_url>https://plus.google.com/118268427775816745234</author_url>
        <language>en</language>
        <profile_photo_url>//lh4.googleusercontent.com/-t__bD01Qin8/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAYtw/mOFdo-jqh3Q/photo.jpg</profile_photo_url>
        <rating>1</rating>
        <text>I not really understand the luggage  locker conception at the station. The station  open 24 hours 7 days/week. Why the luggage  locker close between 11 pm and 6:15 am. No information in the locker ticket at all or big sign we keep close between this time. It is quite annoying. I just missed my midnight bus, because they didn't inform properly... </text>
        <time>1460822353</time>
    </item>
    <item>
        <aspects>
            <item>
                <rating>2</rating>
                <type>overall</type>
            </item>
        </aspects>
        <author_name>Phill Bryant</author_name>
        <author_url>https://plus.google.com/112235521478541652304</author_url>
        <language>en</language>
        <profile_photo_url>//lh3.googleusercontent.com/-bEZu9BgUWf0/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAL3I/WDXyhHkJTwI/photo.jpg</profile_photo_url>
        <rating>4</rating>
        <text>Very busy and slightly confusing station. So many moving parts at this location and if you are not early, you may miss your transport. On one side of the station you have the bus terminal, inside the trains, and the opposite side the city bus, tram, and metro stations. This can be a very overwhelming place for travelers due to how busy everything is, and the signage is not that great. Plenty of food and beverage options for you to indulge in while you wait for your transport and a few charging areas for your electronics.</text>
        <time>1461881949</time>
    </item>
    <item>
        <aspects>
            <item>
                <rating>2</rating>
                <type>overall</type>
            </item>
        </aspects>
        <author_name>Matthew Jackson</author_name>
        <author_url>https://plus.google.com/117583230590493890496</author_url>
        <language>en</language>
        <profile_photo_url>//lh4.googleusercontent.com/-FpFZrejkJEc/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAHM/ll1NioQLudU/photo.jpg</profile_photo_url>
        <rating>4</rating>
        <text>This is a train station, and functions in all the normal capacities of one. There are several stores and restaurants inside, and the ticket office has a number ticket system, and benches. There is free Wi-Fi for 20 minutes. Close to many hotels and a mall. </text>
        <time>1458766145</time>
    </item>
    <item>
        <aspects>
            <item>
                <rating>0</rating>
                <type>overall</type>
            </item>
        </aspects>
        <author_name>Luyao Wang</author_name>
        <author_url>https://plus.google.com/104318619517130227582</author_url>
        <language>en</language>
        <rating>1</rating>
        <text>This luggage place is a fraud. I double checked my arrival time before I entered but by the time I returned they charged me 5 euros more because the time printed on the ticket is at least 40 mins earlier than my point of entry which made me out of the 24hrs limit. If I was not in a hurry to board the train, I would have stayed and argued. But this is how they make money out of travelers, isn't it?</text>
        <time>1460219557</time>
    </item>
    <item>
        <aspects>
            <item>
                <rating>0</rating>
                <type>overall</type>
            </item>
        </aspects>

        <text>I guess it does the job, but you won't want to be hanging around any longer than you need to. Compares badly to St. Pancras.</text>
        <time>1452865576</time>

        <rating>4</rating>
        <text>This is my third time visiting Gump's and after my last visit, I'm not sure how or what they could do to eclipse the level of service I received. I previously posted a favorable review and commented on the poulet chorizo pasta not being as spicy as I expected. I arrived for lunch and was surprised the staff recognized me from my previous visit, and my review. At this time I was informed that if I want my dish to be a little spicier, just let them know and they will take care of it. This surprised me for two reasons: being a busy location, they remembered me; second, they allowed for a dish to be altered, which is not typical in many restaurant locations in France. 

The pasta this time was definitely better than my previous experience, which was still great by any standards. The chicken and the spiciness of the chorizo was perfect. This, accompanied with a very attentive, friendly and welcoming staff, warranted an updated review and an additional star. I highly recommend this restaurant for lunch, or a beverage. Lunch entrÃ©es are very affordable, with several options in the 8 euro range that will satisfy most. Sit outside and enjoy the sun, or venture inside and experience a very nice pub experience.</text>

        <text>A masterpiece. This restaurant is truly something special. When you pull onto the island that this wonderful restaurant calls home, you feel like you have been transported back in time. From the second we walked in the door, we were waited on hand and foot. Our main server, having informed us that he had only worked at Michelin starred restaurants, was incredibly welcoming and informative. He walked my wife and I through the menu, the courses, and the wine flight that we enjoyed along with the meal. The courses built one after another to a beautiful crescendo of flavour and creativity. Hell, we even had house made marshmallows - a first for us. The chef came out to speak with us on two separate occassions, letting us know that he almost married an American girl and that he was happy to have us. He is gracious and supremely talented. Though expensive, Auberge de l'Ile is worth every euro. I hope that they get their third star soon, because they are most deserving. This restaurant truly stands out among the many fabulous restaurants in beautiful Lyon!</text>
        <time>1338326891</time>

        <text>It's just a bar. They do not speak english AT ALL. And the staff (mainly the door mans) are rude.         <text>Fucking joke of a place, more Australian flags than Parliament House complimented by snobby bar staff who refuse to speak or comprehend a word of english despite practically being draped in an Australian flag themselves. I'm not an expert on French law but someone should run a deceptive or misleading conduct claim as this bar represents a serious example of false advertising and I suffered detriment as a result of it. If it was simply called "boat bar" or something similar I would have no problem with it, but it advertises it self as an Australian bar. I guess the name should have been a give away, Uluru is the proper name for Ayers Rock, and "douche bag bar staff in a bar that is not Australian at all" is the correct name for this place.</text>

        <text>After recommondation, went in for a burger.

Staff was friendly and kinda high tech, we placed our order, first said the drinks and directly after that we said what burger we wanted. The english menu wasn't up to date, so there were ingredients on it, that werent available, a pity, but ok :)
Then like 30sec later, still in the middle of our order, the drinks already arrived, pretty sweet :)

We got a burger, it was nice, but semi expensive as least the sides and the drinks, but ok.
